    },
    {
      "id": "CW3_SyNBsyPDq11jMzWJF",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1103.0421041787222,
      "y": 6668.115039778639,
      "width": 1541.2940673828125,
      "height": 1344.3555297851562,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "cRdH",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1860113693,
      "version": 1866,
      "versionNonce": 1336776010,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1768568188278,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Flow:\n1) Exchange Socket takes event \n2) Exchange Socket checks if its leader (Leader service and Redis)\n3) Exchange Socket takes DB connection from Hikari Pool\n4) Writes event to DB event storage\n5) Event is synced with dedicated topic per exchange \n    - Kafka Source Connector or Change Data Capture (CDC) to go DB → Kafka\n    - Potentially use Debezium CDC\n\nArbitrage\n6) Stream take latest data from the dedicated exchange topic \n7) Check the DB for each record and remove records for which we have hit idempotency,\n8) Pushesh the data it to the websocket to which the client is connected.\n\nTimechart \n6) Check the DB for each record and remove records for which we have hit idempotency, \nwe have a table with message_id, timestamp if the message_id is present it means we've processed the event.\n7) Batch consumer takes the data and splits it up Map<Pair, Records>\n8) Take platform/carrier thread from pool and attach a virtual thread to it\n9) Each virtual thread is assigned to persist the event data to the DB,\nto the time-series table\n\nBackground workers:\n1) Leader job is taking data from redis and syncing it to the in-memory boolean flag per instance\n2) Outbox job (if enabled) is taking events from the event storage and republishing to the kafka topics\n3) TimeScaleDB is compressing old data to reduce storage needs\n\nCons:\n WebSocket → DB → Debezium → Kafka (~100-500ms latency)\n\n❌ Added latency - ~100-500ms from DB write to Kafka\n❌ WAL overhead - Increases PostgreSQL I/O\n❌ Complexity - Another component (Debezium/Kafka Connect)\n❌ Schema coupling - DB schema changes affect Kafka messages\n\nWith the original version I control the code and won't have a black box(the connector) that I have to maintain\nAlso with the added latency we can have problems as we scale with 100+ pairs, every millisecond counts\n",
      "fontSize": 28.3022216796875,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Flow:\n1) Exchange Socket takes event \n2) Exchange Socket checks if its leader (Leader service and Redis)\n3) Exchange Socket takes DB connection from Hikari Pool\n4) Writes event to DB event storage\n5) Event is synced with dedicated topic per exchange \n    - Kafka Source Connector or Change Data Capture (CDC) to go DB → Kafka\n    - Potentially use Debezium CDC\n\nArbitrage\n6) Stream take latest data from the dedicated exchange topic \n7) Check the DB for each record and remove records for which we have hit idempotency,\n8) Pushesh the data it to the websocket to which the client is connected.\n\nTimechart \n6) Check the DB for each record and remove records for which we have hit idempotency, \nwe have a table with message_id, timestamp if the message_id is present it means we've processed the event.\n7) Batch consumer takes the data and splits it up Map<Pair, Records>\n8) Take platform/carrier thread from pool and attach a virtual thread to it\n9) Each virtual thread is assigned to persist the event data to the DB,\nto the time-series table\n\nBackground workers:\n1) Leader job is taking data from redis and syncing it to the in-memory boolean flag per instance\n2) Outbox job (if enabled) is taking events from the event storage and republishing to the kafka topics\n3) TimeScaleDB is compressing old data to reduce storage needs\n\nCons:\n WebSocket → DB → Debezium → Kafka (~100-500ms latency)\n\n❌ Added latency - ~100-500ms from DB write to Kafka\n❌ WAL overhead - Increases PostgreSQL I/O\n❌ Complexity - Another component (Debezium/Kafka Connect)\n❌ Schema coupling - DB schema changes affect Kafka messages\n\nWith the original version I control the code and won't have a black box(the connector) that I have to maintain\nAlso with the added latency we can have problems as we scale with 100+ pairs, every millisecond counts\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
