      "text": "Notes:\n2 separate socket - one for event storage, other for processing\nif Kafka is down -> we store the events and replay them\nif DB down -> no event storage but we process events\n\nKafka retention is 1 minute so little data on Broker.\nThe coordinator Kafka brokers will also handle \ndata load. Total 3 brokers.\n\nTimescale -> event storage and analytics\n    all of its data is compressed after 10mins of arrival\n    analytics table is partition by day, so 30-31 partitions\n    we have a job that drops old data and partitions.\n    The idempotency for analytical data consumers will be \n    done via TimeScaleDB as we need to have the \n    persistance of idempotency record and analytical data \n    in one transaction, if its in Redis we'd have to do 2PC\n    to be sure.\n    Also the analytical data is computed via \n    materialized view, all data that is older than 3/5\n    minutes will be served by the view. We can add \n    an index over the materialized view to make it faster.\n for the last 3 mins - aggregations are second by second\n from 3 mins ago to 1 hour ago - aggregations are minute by minute\n from 1 hour ago to 24 hours - aggregations are hour by hour\n from 24 hours ago to 1 month ago - aggregations are day by day\n Each one of these is a separate table with its own materialized view\n and index on top of the view, each is compressed to reduce storage. \n\n    Will have 1 replica.\n\nRedis -> distributed lock and idempotency records\n    idempotency records are there for 2 hours.\n    Need to enable peristance and will have 1 replica.\n\nClient UI -> Opens a socket connection to the \nbackend for a certain crypto pair, when the value is \nupdated on an exchange we push that new data through\nthe socket to the client.\nThe analytical data is fetched via REST GET query\nusing JSON, we can fetch it once the screen opens.\nREST was chosen because its easier to integrate with mobile compared \nto GRPC.\n\nApp -> will have 2 instances running, no duplicate events \nbecause of the leader distributed lock.\n\n\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│  Query: \"Get BTC/USDT prices for last 7 days\"                                         │\n└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n                         ↓\n\n 1. Materialized View (pre-computed aggregations)                                       \n Time saved: 45-90x faster than raw events                                         \n\n                         ↓\n\n2. Indexes on Materialized View (fast lookups)                                         \nTime saved: 25x faster than sequential scan        \n\n                         ↓\n\n3. Compression (20x, reduces I/O)                                    \nTime saved: Less disk I/O, faster reads                                               \n\n                         ↓\n\n4. Daily Partitions (query planning optimization)                                          \nTime saved: PostgreSQL skips irrelevant partitions                                   \n\n                         ↓\n                  Result: ~2ms query time\n         (vs ~5 seconds without optimizations)\n              = 2,500x faster! 🚀",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Notes:\n2 separate socket - one for event storage, other for processing\nif Kafka is down -> we store the events and replay them\nif DB down -> no event storage but we process events\n\nKafka retention is 1 minute so little data on Broker.\nThe coordinator Kafka brokers will also handle \ndata load. Total 3 brokers.\n\nTimescale -> event storage and analytics\n    all of its data is compressed after 10mins of arrival\n    analytics table is partition by day, so 30-31 partitions\n    we have a job that drops old data and partitions.\n    The idempotency for analytical data consumers will be \n    done via TimeScaleDB as we need to have the \n    persistance of idempotency record and analytical data \n    in one transaction, if its in Redis we'd have to do 2PC\n    to be sure.\n    Also the analytical data is computed via \n    materialized view, all data that is older than 3/5\n    minutes will be served by the view. We can add \n    an index over the materialized view to make it faster.\n for the last 3 mins - aggregations are second by second\n from 3 mins ago to 1 hour ago - aggregations are minute by minute\n from 1 hour ago to 24 hours - aggregations are hour by hour\n from 24 hours ago to 1 month ago - aggregations are day by day\n Each one of these is a separate table with its own materialized view\n and index on top of the view, each is compressed to reduce storage. \n\n    Will have 1 replica.\n\nRedis -> distributed lock and idempotency records\n    idempotency records are there for 2 hours.\n    Need to enable peristance and will have 1 replica.\n\nClient UI -> Opens a socket connection to the \nbackend for a certain crypto pair, when the value is \nupdated on an exchange we push that new data through\nthe socket to the client.\nThe analytical data is fetched via REST GET query\nusing JSON, we can fetch it once the screen opens.\nREST was chosen because its easier to integrate with mobile compared \nto GRPC.\n\nApp -> will have 2 instances running, no duplicate events \nbecause of the leader distributed lock.\n\n\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│  Query: \"Get BTC/USDT prices for last 7 days\"                                         │\n└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n                         ↓\n\n 1. Materialized View (pre-computed aggregations)                                       \n Time saved: 45-90x faster than raw events                                         \n\n                         ↓\n\n2. Indexes on Materialized View (fast lookups)                                         \nTime saved: 25x faster than sequential scan        \n\n                         ↓\n\n3. Compression (20x, reduces I/O)                                    \nTime saved: Less disk I/O, faster reads                                               \n\n                         ↓\n\n4. Daily Partitions (query planning optimization)                                          \nTime saved: PostgreSQL skips irrelevant partitions                                   \n\n                         ↓\n                  Result: ~2ms query time\n         (vs ~5 seconds without optimizations)\n              = 2,500x faster! 🚀",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
