      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1768568188278,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Flow:\n\nNormal Socket:\n1) Exchange Socket takes event \n2) Exchange Socket checks if its leader (Leader service and Redis)\n3) Publish event to Kafka\n\nExchange Socket:\n1) Exchange Storer Socket takes event \n2) Exchange Storer Socket checks if its leader (Leader service and Redis)\n3) Exchange Socket takes DB connection from Hikari Pool\n4) Writes event to DB event storage\n\n\nArbitrage (continued from Normal Socket)\n4) Stream take latest data from the dedicated exchange topic \n5) Pushes the data it to the websocket to which the client is connected.\n\nAnalytics (continued from Normal Socket)\n4) Check Redis for each record and remove records for which we have hit idempotency, \nwe have a table with message_id, timestamp if the message_id is present it means we've processed the event.\n5) Batch consumer takes the data and splits it up Map<Pair, Records>\n6) Take platform/carrier thread from pool and attach a virtual thread to it\n7) Each virtual thread is assigned to persist the event data to the DB,\nto the time-series table\n\nBackground workers:\n1) Leader job is taking data from redis and syncing it to the in-memory boolean flag per instance\n2) Outbox job (if enabled) is taking events from the event storage and republishing to the kafka topics\n3) TimeScaleDB is compressing old data to reduce storage needs\n4) TimeScaleDB is deleting old data from analytics and event tables (truncate data + drop partition)\n5) Kafka is dropping old data (events older than 1 minute)\n7) The Monitoring consumer is pushing logs into Vector and then into OpenSearch\n8) TimeScaleDB Materialized View is computed analytics for older data (older than 5 mins)\n\n",
      "fontSize": 28.3022216796875,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Flow:\n\nNormal Socket:\n1) Exchange Socket takes event \n2) Exchange Socket checks if its leader (Leader service and Redis)\n3) Publish event to Kafka\n\nExchange Socket:\n1) Exchange Storer Socket takes event \n2) Exchange Storer Socket checks if its leader (Leader service and Redis)\n3) Exchange Socket takes DB connection from Hikari Pool\n4) Writes event to DB event storage\n\n\nArbitrage (continued from Normal Socket)\n4) Stream take latest data from the dedicated exchange topic \n5) Pushes the data it to the websocket to which the client is connected.\n\nAnalytics (continued from Normal Socket)\n4) Check Redis for each record and remove records for which we have hit idempotency, \nwe have a table with message_id, timestamp if the message_id is present it means we've processed the event.\n5) Batch consumer takes the data and splits it up Map<Pair, Records>\n6) Take platform/carrier thread from pool and attach a virtual thread to it\n7) Each virtual thread is assigned to persist the event data to the DB,\nto the time-series table\n\nBackground workers:\n1) Leader job is taking data from redis and syncing it to the in-memory boolean flag per instance\n2) Outbox job (if enabled) is taking events from the event storage and republishing to the kafka topics\n3) TimeScaleDB is compressing old data to reduce storage needs\n4) TimeScaleDB is deleting old data from analytics and event tables (truncate data + drop partition)\n5) Kafka is dropping old data (events older than 1 minute)\n7) The Monitoring consumer is pushing logs into Vector and then into OpenSearch\n8) TimeScaleDB Materialized View is computed analytics for older data (older than 5 mins)\n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
